The aberrantly-plumaged bird continues. First seen briefly where Tom had it earlier, then later relocated in courtyard between Starbucks Campus Market and H4 parking lot, and ultimately lost in the creek north of H2b parking lot. Seems to have a genetic mutation, rather than a form of Albinism, due to not only lack of pigment on the throat, but also pigment changes in legs. Heard calling, which, interestingly enough, sounded somewhat higher-pitched than the average BLPH. Cool bird! Pics.

Observation Details: Photos to come.  This bird exhibits all the signs of a pure Black Phoebe.  Considerably darker than the presumed hybrid.  Strong demarcation between breast and belly.  Both of these birds hold their wings low when perched and relaxed which is all BLPH.  EAPHs hold their wings even with their tail or above and folded behind their back.  Audio is diagnostic and the hybrid audio I reviewed did not suggest otherwise.

2 birds seen simultaneously, assumed mating pair. Originally listed one "pure" Black Phoebe and one Hybrid Black x Eastern Phoebe but after reviewing photos I am not confident I can determine the degree of hybridization i.e. 1st generation v 2nd generation or even, if there is any hybridization. Neither one presents as a typical Black Phoebe, they both seem to be a little too gray overall, light edging in secondaries and they both have an irregular border in the chest with lighter flecking in the chest and throat. I am throwing my hands up and letting the powers that be decide.

Observation Details: Observed two phoebes in a brief but intense fight. They clashed in midair and tumbled to the ground, with one phoebe pinning down the other. Watched through binoculars, I could see one foot on the head of the other phoebe. They stayed there for about 10 seconds, and continued fighting. A third phoebe joined in and again the phoebes tumbled to the ground, and one phoebe had both pinned underneath it. They all retreated to separate low level branches, each with some ruffled contours. Didn't get pictures of the action, just watched as it happened suddenly.

Observation Details: 2 individuals at this location as discovered by Paul Gordy earlier in the afternoon, a few photos document both birds.   Tried to post many different angles of these birds, including a  few in flight.   It does appear one bird is overall darker in color.  One individual has a small patch of white feathering extending into the dark throat.   Tail motion on both birds was observed to be relatively quick and upward.   EAPH observed a week earlier at Edora Park had a more circular and downward tail motion.   Both of these birds appear to be BLPH's.   They were clearly associating together and foraging on the same midge hatch that all other birds were exploiting.   Will be interesting to see if this is truly a pair and they nest here.

Observation Details: Observed two phoebes in a brief but intense fight. They clashed in midair and tumbled to the ground, with one phoebe pinning down the other. Watched through binoculars, I could see one foot on the head of the other phoebe. They stayed there for about 10 seconds, and continued fighting. A third phoebe joined in and again the phoebes tumbled to the ground, and one phoebe had both pinned underneath it. They all retreated to separate low level branches, each with some ruffled contours. Didn't get pictures of the action, just watched as it happened suddenly.

As we were walking back towards the parking area from Dabbler's Marsh, as we were nearing the new wooden bridges, Steve Nord commented "I think I just heard a Black Phoebe". Steve (and I) then began trying to locate it. Steve saw it first, then I. We both got photos, near the reeds in the little marshy area created to the west of Dabbler's Marsh.  After we'd walked several hundred yards on towards the parking area, Steve heard another BLPH and we both soon spotted it.  We discussed whether or not it might be the same bird but soon concluded that it had to be a 2nd bird, based on the distance we'd walked in just a couple of minutes. About the same time we saw the second Phoebe, I was distracted another direction at the moment when Steve called out Swamp Sparrow and saw it briefly before it disappeared back down into the weeds of the marsh. Sadly, my hearing is not that good any more, so I couldn't hear the sparrow, nor did I see it.

The aberrantly-plumaged bird continues. First seen briefly where Tom had it earlier, then later relocated in courtyard between Starbucks Campus Market and H4 parking lot, and ultimately lost in the creek north of H2b parking lot. Seems to have a genetic mutation, rather than a form of Albinism, due to not only lack of pigment on the throat, but also pigment changes in legs. Heard calling, which, interestingly enough, sounded somewhat higher-pitched than the average BLPH. Cool bird! Pics.

We were stood on the path scanning the shorebirds. It had been a good half hour when a medium-sized dark flycatcher suddenly flew in from the east and landed on the dead tree hanging out of the bank in front of us. We all quickly got optics on it as it looked interesting. For a second I pondered whether it was perhaps a pewee but clapping eyes on it through my scope at 15m range, it immediately became obvious that it wasn't with Dave being the first off the mark to call it a Black Phoebe!  Overall blackish back, head and chest, white belly with cinnamon wingbars indicating a juvenile bird. Frequently giving whistled chip calls.   Bird performed a couple of sallies from the log before flying up into the trees then behind us and south over them continuing to call but eventually going too far to be heard. In total, bird was around for about a minute.  What a bird!  RBAs and community server: https://discord.gg/2f38pEZ

Observation Details: Observed two phoebes in a brief but intense fight. They clashed in midair and tumbled to the ground, with one phoebe pinning down the other. Watched through binoculars, I could see one foot on the head of the other phoebe. They stayed there for about 10 seconds, and continued fighting. A third phoebe joined in and again the phoebes tumbled to the ground, and one phoebe had both pinned underneath it. They all retreated to separate low level branches, each with some ruffled contours. Didn't get pictures of the action, just watched as it happened suddenly.

Photos to come.  This bird exhibits all the signs of a pure Black Phoebe.  Considerably darker than the presumed hybrid.  Strong demarcation between breast and belly.  Both of these birds hold their wings low when perched and relaxed which is all BLPH.  EAPHs hold their wings even with their tail or above and folded behind their back.  Audio is diagnostic and the hybrid audio I reviewed did not suggest otherwise.

Locality: Calle de Los Agrinemsors, Hitchcock Canyon

Observation Details: 2 birds seen simultaneously, assumed mating pair. Originally listed one "pure" Black Phoebe and one Hybrid Black x Eastern Phoebe but after reviewing photos I am not confident I can determine the degree of hybridization i.e. 1st generation v 2nd generation or even, if there is any hybridization. Neither one presents as a typical Black Phoebe, they both seem to be a little too gray overall, light edging in secondaries and they both have an irregular border in the chest with lighter flecking in the chest and throat. I am throwing my hands up and letting the powers that be decide.

Observation Details: lifer!! Heard only and id by merlin before the hike at garden, but only saw it as we were nearing exit at end of visit, where it was flycatching in the grass patch in the middle of garden. Very similar in shape, call, size, and foraging behavior as eastern Phoebe, dropping from short tree in middle of lawn down to grass to catch flies, sometimes briefly hovering. Stayed at that spot for 2 mins, before wandering around perimeter of garden and going on higher branches.
